Nov 18 2009	Not so sweet a suite...	My daughter and I overnighted at Hotel Fusion last week. Needing two beds, I booked a &quot;suite&quot;, thinking it would be more spacious than one room with two double beds. At check-in, I was pleasantly surprised to hear we'd been upgraded to &quot;one of the most expensive suites in the hotel&quot;. I guess the definition of &quot;suite&quot; is relative. The door to the room entered into the poorly lit, narrow sitting area (I figured 8' X 10'), in which was crammed a desk w/ chair, mini-refrigerator, daybed/couch, and another chair and endtable. The sitting area was separated from the (I figured 10' X 10') bedroom by a doorless cut-out in the wall, which allowed little to no privacy in either space. Into the bedroom was shoehorned a queen bed, two night stands (one of which had a clock that was an hour behind), and a heating unit with what appeared to be some kind of food/beverage tray permanently affixed to the top. All of which left less than 2' to maneuver on two sides of the bed, and a bit more on the side with the door into the bathroom. Small flat-screen TVs hung from a wall in each room, and the one window opened to the three other exterior walls on the inside of the building (I wouldn't call it an atrium, though). Curiously, the bathroom was the most spacious of the three rooms in the suite. It had a single pedestal sink, toilet, and tub/shower.That all said, the room was clean, the bed and furniture reasonably comfortable, and the common areas of the hotel attractive and welcoming. Breakfast wasn't much, but more than we had in a similar hotel in the city a few years ago. And the location.... hard to beat really. I might recommend it on that basis alone. But, this review should leave no question as to what impressed (is unimpressed a word?) us most about Hotel Fusion. Our experience might have been different had the hotel's website included photos of the suites so we'd known what to expect.	
Nov 11 2009 	Nice room good location	Hotel Fusion is right in town, in Ellis Street, and although the street is relatively busy the windows are double glazed which cuts the noise right down (and you can open them if you want fresh air, which is a bonus). We upgraded to a king room, as we'd heard the rooms can be a bit small. The room was big and very comfortable, nicely furnished and quite modern. There is a nightclub next door which is part of the hotel but we didn't hear any noise at all, either from music or the crowd queueing to get in, and our room was at the front overlooking the street. Staff were friendly but not overly so, airport transfer is cheap and efficient - the BART is close by but when we were there the station lifts were out of order and there are a lot of steps! Not much fun with heavy suitcases. The hotel has free Wi-Fi in the reception area and they have a business centre if you want to use internet. They also have a concierge desk if you want tours or transport booked. The hotel doesn't have a restaurant so no room service is available. There are plenty of restaurants in the area so that's not really a problem recommend Millennium in Hotel California). For a standard hotel it's pretty good and if we ever go back to San Francisco we'd stay at Hotel Fusion again no problem.	
