Feb 16 2009 	Watch Out for Homeless People	My girlfriend and I got a great deal on a trip to San Francisco, including three nights at the Hotel Fusion. I'd been to SF before, so I knew that it was a great location. We read previous reviews about the not-so-stellar breakfast, but decided we could live with it. The hotel is easy to get to and clean. Our room was spotless, with the exception of some food stains on the curtain. The coffee pot was nowhere near an outlet, so we had to do some rearranging. Our room was on the second floor facing the street. Many people complained about noise at this hotel, but we didn't find that to be a problem. With the windows closed, we couldn't hear the people partying at the club downstairs on Saturday night.However, we had one big problem with the hotel: the staff and their lack of concern for their guests. On our first day at the hotel we found ourselves on the elevator with a homeless man who was wandering around the hotel. As two young female travelers, we didn't like the idea of random homeless people traipsing about the place. (We're from New York City, so we deal with homeless people everyday. But not feeling safe in a hotel is another matter entirely.) We immediately went downstairs to see the concierge about the matter. He called a colleague of his, who went upstairs to investigate. Apparently, homeless people come into the building frequently. Instead of asking the man to leave, the hotel staff person simply said to him, &quot;Hey, you scared those girls.&quot; Not exactly the response we were looking for. Nevertheless, from that point on, we took the stairs.Two days later, while waiting in the lobby for a tour bus to pick us up, a homeless woman wandered in ranting about satan and pop culture. Several hotel guests who didn't speak English were standing near the door. The concierge walked over to their bags to make sure nothing was stolen, but he didn't ask the homeless woman to leave the building. This is just not acceptable.I understand that homelessness is a huge problem in San Francisco. I understand that I cannot compare the homeless culture in every city to that of New York City. However, there should be borders - and a hotel should be one of those borders. I did not feel safe in this hotel and am not likely to return.	
